#1

if (!file.exists("met_all.gz"))
  download.file(
    url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/USCbiostats/data-science-data/master/02_met/met_all.gz",
    destfile = "met_all.gz",
    method   = "libcurl",
    timeout  = 60
    )
met <- data.table::fread("met_all.gz")

#2:

met <- met[temp >= -17][elev == 9999.0, elev :=NA]
met[, week := week(as.Date(paste(year, month, day, sep = "-")))]
met <- met[week == min(week, na.rm = TRUE)]
met_avg <- met[, .(
  temp      = mean(temp, na.rm = TRUE),
  rh        = mean(rh, na.rm = TRUE),
  wind.sp   = mean(wind.sp, na.rm = TRUE),
  vis.dist  = mean(vis.dist, na.rm = TRUE),
  dew.point = mean(dew.point, na.rm = TRUE),
  lat       = mean(lat, na.rm = TRUE),
  lon       = mean(lon, na.rm = TRUE),
  elev      = mean(elev, na.rm = TRUE)
), by = "USAFID"]
met_avg$region <- ifelse(met_avg$lon > -98 & met_avg$lat > 39.71, "north east",
                  ifelse(met_avg$lon > -98 & met_avg$lat < 39.71, "south east",
                  ifelse(met_avg$lon <= -98 & met_avg$lat > 39.71, "north west",
                         "south west")))
met_avg$elev_cat <- ifelse(met_avg$elev> 252, "high", "low")
table(met_avg$region)

north east north west south east south west 
       484        146        649        297

met_avg %>%
  filter(!is.na(elev_cat)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = elev_cat, fill = region), position = "dodge") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "PuOr") +
  labs(
    title = "Number of weather stations by elevation category and region",
    x = "Elevation category",
    y = "Count"
  ) +
  theme_bw()

The south east region has by far the most low-elevation stations, while the north east region has a strong presence at both elevation levels. The north west has relatively few stations in total, especially at low elevation.

#6:

met_avg %>%
  filter(!is.na(dew.point)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = region, y = dew.point, fill = region)) +
  stat_summary(fun.data = "mean_sdl", geom = "errorbar") +
  stat_summary(fun.data = "mean_sdl")

South east has the highest average dew point (~21), with relatively small variation compared to others. North east also has a moderately high dew point (~16). South west and especially north west show lower average dew points (~12â13), but also much wider error bars, meaning dew point values there are more variable.Overall, there are regional differences in dew point, with southern and eastern regions tending to have higher averages, while western regions have more variability.

#7

met_avg2<-met_avg[!is.na(rh)]
top10 <- met_avg2[rank(-rh) <= 10]
rh_pal = colorNumeric(c('lightblue','purple','lightyellow'), domain=met_avg2$rh)
leaflet(met_avg2) %>%
  addProviderTiles("OpenStreetMap") %>%
  addCircles(
    lat = ~lat, lng = ~lon,
    color = ~rh_pal(rh),
    label = ~paste0(round(rh, 2), " rh"),
    opacity = 1, fillOpacity = 1, radius = 500
  ) %>%
  addMarkers(
    lat = ~lat, lng = ~lon,
    label = ~paste0(round(rh, 2), " rh"),
    data = top10
  ) %>%
  addLegend(
    position = "bottomleft",
    pal = rh_pal,
    values = met_avg2$rh,
    title = "Relative Humidity",
    opacity = 1
  )

The map gives a geographic view of relative humidity across the U.S., showing regional contrasts between dry western areas and more humid eastern/southern areas, with the most humid stations marked by blue pins.

#8

temp_region <- met_avg %>%
  group_by(region) %>%
  summarise(avg_temp = mean(temp, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")

print(temp_region)
